{"title_page": "Council of British Druid Orders", "text_new": "[[File:Rave in the Henge 2005.jpg|thumb|The 2005 mid-summer festival at [[Stonehenge]]]] \nThe '''Council of British Druid Orders''' is a neo-pagan group that holds ceremonies at [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wallis|first=Robert|title=Shamans/Neo-Shamans: Contested Ecstasies, Alternative Archaeologies, and Contemporary Pagans|url=https://www.questia.com/read/103955673/shamans-neo-shamans-contested-ecstasies-alternative|year=2003|publisher=Routledge {{Subscription required|via=[[Questia]]}} |page=145}}</ref> The Council's founder, Tim Sebastian, used the title, \"Archdruid of Wiltshire, Chosen Chief of the Secular Order of Druids, Conservation Officer for the Council of British Druid Orders and Bard of the Gorsedd of Caer Abiri (Avebury).\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/jun/22/johnvidal|title=The weird and wonderful return to get stoned at Stonehenge|last=Vidal|first=John|date=22 June 2000|work=Guardian|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>  \n\nThe group is best known for presiding at mid-summer festivals held since 1999.<ref>\"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/23/AR2009062303378.html Time Zones: Five Hours of Solstice Reverence and Revelry at Stonehenge],\" ''Washington Post'', June 24, 2009.</ref> Up to 24,000 have attended.<ref>\"[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-463607/As-dawn-broke-longest-day-year-24-000-witches-pagans-druids-descend-Stonehenge.html As dawn broke on the longest day of the year, 24,000 witches, pagans and druids descend on Stonehenge],\" ''Daily Mail'', 22 June 2007.</ref> These festivals are a successor to the [[Stonehenge Free Festival]] that was held from 1974 to 1984.\n\n==Prominent members==\n* [[Arthur Uther Pendragon]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cobdo.org.uk/html/about_cobdo.html Official Website of the Council of British Druid Orders]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120208111856/http://www.secularorderofdruids.org/ Secular Order of Druids] \n* [http://www.grahamharvey.org/Tim.htm Graham Harvey- Tribute to Tim Sebastian]\n\n[[Category:Neopagan religious organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Neo-druid orders]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Rave in the Henge 2005.jpg|thumb|The 2005 mid-summer festival at [[Stonehenge]]]] \nThe '''Council of British Druid Orders''' is a neo-pagan group that holds ceremonies at [[Stonehenge]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wallis|first=Robert|title=Shamans/Neo-Shamans: Contested Ecstasies, Alternative Archaeologies, and Contemporary Pagans|url=https://www.questia.com/read/103955673/shamans-neo-shamans-contested-ecstasies-alternative|year=2003|publisher=Routledge {{Subscription required|via=[[Questia]]}} |page=145}}</ref> The Council's founder, Tim Sebastian, used the title, \"Archdruid of Wiltshire, Chosen Chief of the Secular Order of Druids, Conservation Officer for the Council of British Druid Orders and Bard of the Gorsedd of Caer Abiri (Avebury).\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/jun/22/johnvidal|title=The weird and wonderful return to get stoned at Stonehenge|last=Vidal|first=John|date=22 June 2000|work=Guardian|accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref>  \n\nThe group is best known for presiding at mid-summer festivals held since 1999.<ref>\"[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/23/AR2009062303378.html Time Zones: Five Hours of Solstice Reverence and Revelry at Stonehenge],\" ''Washington Post'', June 24, 2009.</ref> Up to 24,000 have attended.<ref>\"[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-463607/As-dawn-broke-longest-day-year-24-000-witches-pagans-druids-descend-Stonehenge.html As dawn broke on the longest day of the year, 24,000 witches, pagans and druids descend on Stonehenge],\" ''Daily Mail'', 22 June 2007.</ref> These festivals are a successor to the [[Stonehenge Free Festival]] that was held from 1974 to 1984.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}