{"title_page": "Foxy Brown (rapper)", "text_new": "{{about|the rapper|the reggae singer|Foxy Brown (singer)}}\n{{short description|American rapper, actress, and model from New York}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Foxy Brown\n| image              = Foxy brown-03-mika.jpg\n| caption            = Marchand in 1998\n| alias              = {{hlist|Dutchess|Fox Boogie|Ill Na Na<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/374556|title=Dutchess (2)|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref>}}\n| birth_name         = Inga DeCarlo Fung Marchand<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-dad-was-us-trinidad-immigration/|title=Foxy Brown Reveals That Her Dad Was Stopped From Returning To The U.S.|website=Essence.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\"entertainment weekly\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Scott|last2=Serpick|first2=Evan|title=Lil' Brown & Co.|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,280191,00.html|periodical=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|issue=586|date=2001-03-09|accessdate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1978|9|6}}{{refn|An arrest report by the [[Broward County Sheriff's Office]] dated February 16, 2007, listed her birth year as 1978.<ref name=\"Smoking Gun\"/> An article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' from September 8, 2007, stated: \"Ms. Brown, who turned 29 on Thursday [September 6], had tried to conceal her identity by writing her name as Enga rather than Inga, and giving her date of birth as 1980 rather than 1978.\"<ref name=\"Contrite\"/> The website [[AllMusic]] lists her birth date as September 6, 1979.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> An ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' article from March 9, 2001 appears to support the 1979 birth year. In her song \"I Don't Need Nobody\", Marchand raps \"1978 / The year I was born\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UfUlZ7FCGCk \"I Don't Need Nobody\"] on YouTube</ref>|group=nb}}\n| birth_place        =  [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* model\n* actress\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active       = 1995\u2013present\n| home_town          = \n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* Black Rose {{small|(current)}}\n* [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]\n* [[Entertainment One Music|Koch]]\n* [[S. Carter Records|S. Carter]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Rush]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n* [[Violator (company)|Violator]]{{small| (former)}}\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[The Firm (hip hop group)|The Firm]]\n*[[DJ Clue]]\n*[[Jay-Z]]\n*[[N.O.R.E.]]\n*[[Spragga Benz]]\n*[[Trackmasters]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj]]}}\n| module = {{Infobox person\n| child = yes \n| partner = [[Kurupt]] (1999\u20132000)<br>[[Spragga Benz]] (2001)\n| children = 1\n}}\n}}\n'''Inga DeCarlo Fung Marchand''' (born September 6, 1978), better known by her stage name '''Foxy Brown''', is an American rapper. After signing to [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]] in 1996, she released her debut album, ''[[Ill Na Na]]'', that same year, and was also part of the short-lived rap group [[The Firm (hip hop group)|the Firm]].\n\nHer second album ''[[Chyna Doll (album)|Chyna Doll]]'', arrived in 1999, and her third, the Grammy-nominated ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]'', in 2001.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/foxy-brown | title=Foxy Brown| date=2018-05-22}}</ref>  [[The Album (The Firm album)|The Firm's sole album]] arrived in 1997. Since 2001, she has featured on songs, but has not released any albums. In 2003, she left Def Jam and cancelled the release of her ''Ill Na Na 2'' album, but returned in 2005 once [[Jay-Z]], then the label's president and CEO, signed her again to begin work on her new album ''[[Black Roses (Foxy Brown album)|Black Roses]]''. Her [[mixtape]] ''[[Brooklyn Don Diva]]'' was released in May 2008, and her visual album, ''[[King Soon Come (Foxy Brown album)|King Soon Come]]'', was slated for 2019 release.<ref name=\"Winslow\">{{Cite news|url=https://allhiphop.com/2017/03/02/rapper-foxy-brown-gives-birth-baby-girl/|title=Rapper Foxy Brown Gives Birth To A Baby Girl|last=Winslow|first=Mike|accessdate=August 20, 2017|quote=Foxy Brown is working on her latest album, King Soon Come.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theblackloop.com/wow-foxy-brown-just-gave-birth-baby-girl-shocks-everyone/|title=Wow! Foxy Brown Just Gave Birth To A Baby Girl! Shocks Everyone!|last=Loop|first=The Black|accessdate=August 20, 2017|quote=Congrats to Foxy Brown! Foxy Brown is working on her latest album, King Soon Come.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822175050/https://www.theblackloop.com/wow-foxy-brown-just-gave-birth-baby-girl-shocks-everyone/|archive-date=2017-08-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Madden\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/09/happy-birthday-foxy-brown/|title=Happy Birthday, Foxy Brown!|last=Madden|first=Sidney|accessdate=September 30, 2017|quote=To date, Foxy is said to be working on her fourth studio album, King Soon Come.}}</ref><ref name=\"Clark\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-shares-first-photo-her-adorable-baby-girl|title=Foxy Brown Shares The First Photo Of Her Adorable Baby Girl|last=Clark|first=Danielle Kwateng|accessdate=September 30, 2017|quote=Currently she's working on her fourth studio album.}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===1995\u20131997: Early career, ''Ill Na Na'' and The Firm===\nWhile still a teenager, Brown won a talent contest in the [[Park Slope]] neighborhood of Brooklyn, New York. Members of the production team [[Trackmasters]] who were working on [[LL Cool J]]'s ''[[Mr. Smith (album)|Mr. Smith]]'' album were in attendance that night and were impressed enough to invite Brown to rap over \"[[I Shot Ya]].\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Bush|first= John|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29875|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2008|accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref> She followed this debut with appearances on several [[RIAA certification|RIAA platinum and gold singles]] from other artists, including remixes of songs \"You're Makin' Me High\" by [[Toni Braxton]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> Brown was also featured on the soundtrack to the 1996 film ''[[The Nutty Professor (1996 film)|The Nutty Professor]]'', on the songs \"Touch Me Tease Me\" by [[Case (singer)|Case]] and \"[[Ain't No Nigga]]\" by [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. [{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r236237|pure_url=yes}} \"The Nutty Professor\" \u2013 overview]. [[AllMusic]]: c. 1996.</ref> She became an instant sensation due to being very talented and rapping provocatively at such a young age. The immediate success led to a label bidding war at the beginning of 1996, and in March, [[Def Jam Records]] won and added the then 17-year-old rapper to their roster.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] has been said to have wanted her to join his rap group \u201c[[Junior M.A.F.I.A.]]\u2019 However, due to him no being able to win the bidding war, he settled for Lil\u2019 Kim instead. In 1996, Foxy Brown, Lil' Kim, Da Brat, and Total got together for the recording of Bad Boy's remix of \"No One Else\". This was the only track that Lil' Kim and Foxy Brown appeared on together, the two were friends at the time.\n\nIn 1996, Brown released her debut album ''[[Ill Na Na]]'' to mixed reviews but strong sales. The album sold over 109,000 copies in the first week, and debuted at #7 on the Billboard 200 album charts.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> The album was heavily produced by Trackmasters, and featured guest appearances from [[Jay-Z]], [[Blackstreet]], [[Method Man]], and [[Kid Capri]].<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. [{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r243995|pure_url=yes}} \"Ill Na Na\" \u2013 overview]. [[AllMusic]]</ref> The album was [[RIAA certification|platinum]] and launched two hit singles: \"[[Get Me Home (song)|Get Me Home]]\" (featuring [[Blackstreet]]) and \"I'll Be\" (featuring [[Jay-Z]]).<ref name=\"single charts\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Billboard singles|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29875|pure_url=yes}}|work= [[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2007-10-10}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of ''Ill Na Na'', Brown joined fellow New York-based hip hop artists, [[Nas]], [[AZ (rapper)|AZ]], and [[Nature (rapper)|Nature]] to form the [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] known as [[The Firm (hip hop group)|The Firm]]. The album was released via [[Aftermath Records]] and was produced and recorded by the collective team of [[Dr. Dre]], [[the Trackmasters]], and [[Steve Stoute|Steve \"Commissioner\" Stoute]], then of [[Violator Entertainment]]. An early form of The Firm appeared on \"Affirmative Action\" from Nas' second album ''[[It Was Written]]''. A remix of the song and several group [[Freestyle rap|freestyles]] were on the album ''[[The Album (The Firm album)|Nas, Foxy Brown, AZ, and Nature Present The Firm: The Album]]''.<ref name=\"firm\">{{cite web|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|title=The Firm \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p276628|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> The album entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart at #1.<ref name=\"The Firm \u2013 Billboard Albums\">{{cite web|title=The Firm \u2013 Billboard Albums|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p276628|pure_url=yes}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1997, she joined the [[spring break]] festivities hosted by MTV in Panama City, Florida, among other performers including rapper [[Snoop Dogg]], pop group [[The Spice Girls]], and rock band [[Stone Temple Pilots]].<ref name=\"MTV News\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown, Spice Girls, Snoop, STP Do Spring Break|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429118/19970313/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-03-13|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> Later, she joined the Smokin' Grooves tour hosted by the [[House of Blues]] with the headlining rap group [[Cypress Hill]], along with other performers like [[Erykah Badu]], [[The Roots]], [[OutKast]], and [[The Pharcyde]], the tour set to begin in [[Boston, Massachusetts]], in the summer of 1997.<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite news|title=Cypress Hill, Erykah Badu, Foxy Brown Join Smokin' Grooves Tour|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425328/19970408/badu_erykah.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-04-08|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> However, after missing several dates in the tour, she left it.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Bows Out of Smokin' Grooves|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429114/19970714/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-07-14|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===1998\u20131999: ''Chyna Doll''===\n''Chyna Doll'' was released in January 1999 and debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200 Album charts<ref>{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Delays second album, Talks Diversity|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429106/19981207/foxy_brown.jhtml | publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1998-12-07|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> which sold 173,000 copies in its opening week.<ref name=\"Boehlert\">{{cite news|last=Boehlert|first=Eric|title=Silk the Shocker|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/foxybrown2/articles/story/5923314/shock_the_shocker|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1999-02-03|accessdate=2008-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104164212/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/foxybrown2/articles/story/5923314/shock_the_shocker|archive-date=2008-01-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, its sales quickly declined in later weeks.<ref name=\"Promis\">{{cite web|last=Promis|first= Jose F.|title=\"Chyna Doll\" \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r380219|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2007-10-11}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"Hot Spot\", failed to enter the top 50 of the ''Billboard'' pop charts, as did the follow-up single, \"I Can't\" (featuring [[Total (group)|Total]]). ''Chyna Doll'' has been certified [[RIAA Certification|platinum]] after surpassing one million copies sold in shippments.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Gold and Platinum|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Foxy%20Brown&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=12&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=25|publisher=[[RIAA]]|accessdate=2008-02-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151852/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Foxy%20Brown&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=12&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=25|archivedate=2015-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1999, Brown stated on ''[[The Ricki Lake Show]]'' that she would appear in the 2000 action film ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]].'' The role was recast after Brown's legal troubles; actress [[Lucy Liu]] took Brown's place.\n\n===2000\u20132003: ''Broken Silence'' and ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever''===\n{{Main|Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)}}\nIn 2001, Brown released ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]''. The single  \"BK Anthem\" showcased Brown changing to a \"street\" image and giving a tribute to her hometown, Brooklyn, and to famous rappers such as [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] and [[Jay Z]]. The first single from the album was \"[[Oh Yeah (Foxy Brown song)|Oh Yeah]]\", which featured her then-boyfriend, Jamaican [[dancehall]] artist [[Spragga Benz]].<ref name=\"Spragga Benz allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|title=Spragga Benz \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p173453|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2003|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> The track \"Na Na Be Like\" was produced by Kenya Fame Flames Miller and Nokio from [[Dru Hill]]. \"Na Na Be Like\" was also on the ''Blue Streak Soundtrack''.\n\nThe album debuted on the Billboard Charts at #5, selling 130,000 units its first week. Like previous albums, ''Broken Silence'' also sold over 500,000 records and was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[RIAA]].\n\nIn the same year, Brown recorded a song for the action-comedy film ''[[Rush Hour 2]]'', ''[[Rush Hour 2 (soundtrack)|Blow My Whistle]]'', which is a collaboration with [[Japanese-American]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Hikaru Utada]], and was written by Utada herself alongside [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Chad Hugo]]. The song is included on [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]'s ''[[Rush Hour 2 (soundtrack)|Rush Hour 2 Soundtrack]]'', which peaked the 11th spot on both the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and also the first on the [[Top Soundtracks]]. \"Blow My Whistle\" was produced by [[The Neptunes]].<ref name=\"Rush Hour 2\">''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0266915/soundtrack Rush Hour 2]'' on IMDB.com</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Brown returned to the music scene briefly with her single \"[[Stylin']]\", whose remix featured rappers [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], her brother Gavin, [[Loon (rapper)|Loon]], and [[N.O.R.E.]] It was to be the first single from her upcoming album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever''.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Cam'ron, Foxy Brown, N.O.R.E. On Illest Tour|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1457742/20020923/cam_ron.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2002-09-23|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> The next year, she was featured on [[DJ Kayslay]]'s single \"Too Much for Me\" from his ''Street Sweeper's Volume One Mixtape''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=DJ Kay Slay Says It's Mo' Artists, Mo' Problems On Legit CDs|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472003/20030520/dj_kayslay.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2003-05-20|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> She also appeared on [[Luther Vandross]]' final studio album ''[[Dance with My Father (album) (redirect)|Dance with My Father]]''.<ref name=\"Jeffries 2003\">{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=Dance with My Father \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r642211|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2003|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> That April, Brown appeared on popular New York radio DJ [[Wendy Williams (radio hostess)|Wendy Williams]]' radio show, and revealed the details of her relationships with [[Lyor Cohen]], president of [[Def Jam Recordings]] at the time, and [[Sean Combs|Sean \"P. Diddy\" Combs]]. Brown accused both of illegally trading her recording masters. She also announced that Cohen had cancelled promotion for her fourth album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever'' over personal disagreements.<ref name=\"Promotion Cancelled\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown's \"Ill Na Na 2\" Shelved Indefinitely|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12037470|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=2003-04-22|accessdate=2008-02-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629144901/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12037470|archivedate=2011-06-29}}</ref> Therefore, \"Stylin'\" was released on the compilation album ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] Presents: Hip Hop Hits Vol. 6'' in December 2002.<ref name=\"Kellman 2002\">{{cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|title=\"The Source Presents: Hip Hop Hits, Vol. 6\" \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r620169|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2002|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132006: ''Black Roses''===\nUpon leaving [[Def Jam Recordings]] after her disappointment in the cancelled promotion of her studio album, ''[[Ill Na Na 2: The Fever]]'', Brown began recording in late 2004. Months after, she reunited with [[Jay Z]] after performing dates on his Best of Both World Tours. After signing back to Def Jam under his regime, Brown and Jay Z began work on ''Black Roses'' with production by [[The Neptunes]], [[Kanye West]], [[Timbaland]], [[Trackmasters]], and [[Dave Kelly (producer)|Dave Kelly]]. Brown confirmed guest appearances by [[Barrington Levy]], [[Dido (singer)|Dido]], [[Luther Vandross]], [[Mos Def]], [[Baby Cham]], [[Spragga Benz]], [[Shyne]], [[Big Daddy Kane]], [[Rakim]], [[KRS-One]], [[Roxanne Shante]], and [[Jay Z]] although it is uncertain whether all will make the final cut for the album.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} After suffering from a hearing loss and pushing back release dates for the album, Brown left Def Jam for the second time and launched an independent record label, [[Black Rose Entertainment]], in a distribution deal with [[Koch Records]]. According to Brown, two albums worth of material had been recorded between 2004 and 2007 and she planned to release some of the material onto the street album, ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]''.<ref name=\"Baller Status\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2007/08/14/foxy-brown-leaves-def-jam-inks-label-deal-through-koch// |publisher=Baller Status |date=August 14, 2007 |author=Allen Starbury |title=Foxy Brown Leaves Def Jam; Inks Label Deal Through Koch}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, Brown announced that the title for her upcoming album would be ''Black Roses'', explaining, \"My best friend [[Barrington Levy]] has a song called \"Black Roses.\" He's been traveling all over the world and never seen a black rose in no other garden. When he found his black rose, he knew that shit was special. Y'all niggas can have all the female rappers in the world, but there's only one black rose. I feel that's me.\"<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1493486/20041105/foxy_brown.jhtml/ |publisher=MTV |date=November 5, 2004 |author=Shaheem Reid |title=Foxy Brown Planning Comeback With Help From Jay-Z, Shyne}}</ref> In November 2004, Brown announced that she would be the first artist signed to Jay-Z's upcoming imprint record label [[S. Carter Records]]. Rather than launching the imprint, though, Jay-Z became the new president and CEO of [[Def Jam Records]], where he signed Brown as one of the first artists on his new roster.<ref name=\"SOHH\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/10173 |publisher=SOHH |date=November 6, 2006 |author=Dick Johnson |title=Foxy Brown Served \"Black Roses,\" Gets Axed From Label? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201218/http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/10173 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> On December 8, 2005, Brown announced she had experienced severe and sudden hearing loss]in both ears and she had not heard another person's voice in six months. Brown put ''Black Roses'' aside during this time.<ref name=\"VH1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1518260/20051215/foxy_brown.jhtml |publisher=VH1 |date=December 15, 2005 |author=Chris Harris |title=Foxy Brown Says She Hasn't Heard A Thing For Six Months}}</ref> In June 2006, Brown said her hearing had been restored through surgery and she was planning to resume recording. Her label did not set a release date, but hoped the album would be out by the end of 2006. They were unsure if the title ''Black Roses'' would be kept.<ref name=\"VH12\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1535227/20060627/foxy_brown.jhtml |publisher=VH1 |date=June 28, 2006 |author=Shaheem Reid |title=Foxy Brown Returns: Deafness Cured, She's Back To Work}}</ref> In November 2006, there was speculation that Jay-Z was disappointed in Foxy Brown's \"lack of productivity on the album\" and was planning to drop her from the Def Jam label. The planned December 2006 release of ''Black Roses'' was cancelled.<ref name=\"SOHH\"/>\n\nOn May 22, 2007, Black Hand Entertainment announced a management deal with Brown, with Chaz Williams as her manager. No release date was set for ''Black Roses'', but Brown said the album was nearly complete.<ref name=\"SOHH2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/11684/1 |publisher=VH1 |date=May 23, 2007 |author=Anthony Roberts |title=Foxy Brown Under New Management, Ordered To Submit DNA Sample In Assault Case |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930204727/http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/11684/1 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> A release date of September 6, 2007, was announced two days later.<ref name=\"Mariel Concepcion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1051937/foxy-brown-readies-comeback-with-black-roses |work=Billboard |date=May 24, 2007 |author=Mariel Concepcion |title=Foxy Brown Readies Comeback With 'Black Roses'}}</ref> On August 16, 2007, Black Hand Entertainment announced that Brown would leave Def Jam to launch an independent record label, [[Black Rose Entertainment]], distributed by [[Koch Records]]. A street album, ''[[Brooklyn Don Diva]]'', was scheduled with a release date of December 4, 2007, but was delayed until May 13, 2008.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1049862/foxy-brown-joins-koch-records |work=Billboard |date=August 15, 2007 |author=Hillary Crosley |title=Foxy Brown Joins Koch Records}}</ref>\n\n''Black Roses'' release has been pushed back several times. In May 2005, the release date was set for July 26, 2005. The next month, it was pushed back to August 23, 2005. In July 2006, Black Roses had a December 2006 release. In May 2007, Brown announced the album would be released on September 6, 2007. As of August 2007, ''Black Roses'' was rumored to be set for a 2008 release date, but nothing was further confirmed. Brown was expected to first release the street album ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]'' on May 13, 2008, following her April 2008 release from prison. In an interview with Billboard.com, Brown stated that the album is back on track and she personally wants in to drop in August or September 2011, however due to no material being released on the planned dates, yet again the album was shelved.\n\n===2007\u2013present: ''Brooklyn's Don Diva'' and ''King Soon Come''===\nBrown signed to [[Koch Records]] in August 2007.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> ''Brooklyn's Don Diva'', was released as a street album on May 13, 2008, after many delays triggered by her prison sentence. It contains two previously unreleased  songs from her shelved album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever.'' The album peaked at #83 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, #8 on the [[Independent Albums]] chart, and #5 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn's Don Diva > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r1239535|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-08-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Brown released the diss track \u201cMassacre\u201d, a response to Lil\u2019 Kim's \u201cBlack Friday\u201d. On August 14, 2012, Foxy Brown appeared as a special featured guest on [[Nicki Minaj]]'s [[Pink Friday Tour]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Universalmusic.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.universalmusic.com/news/detail/2147 |title=VIDEO: Nicki Minaj Speaks on Foxy Brown after her \"Pink Friday Tour\" |publisher=Universal Music |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref> Rapper [[AZ (rapper)|AZ]] hinted that she is working on new material with Nicki Minaj.<ref name=\"Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by Nadine Graham Comments\">{{cite web|author=Nadine Graham Comments |url=http://www.theboombox.com/2012/10/22/az-the-firm/ |title=The Firm's 'The Album' 15 Years Later: AZ Speaks on Group's First & Final Project |publisher=The Boombox |date=2012-10-22 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref> On August 15, 2013, Foxy Brown appeared on MTV Rapfix and announced her fourth studio album tentatively titled \"Bandz Up\" and a single of the same name, produced by Joe Milly, which was set to be released December 24, 2013, but was not released for unknown reasons. In August 2018, Brown made her first official guest appearance since 2009 on \"Coco Chanel\" from Nicki Minaj's fourth studio album ''[[Queen (Nicki Minaj album)|Queen]]''. Brown is currently back to work on her upcoming 4th visual studio album ''King Soon Come '' <ref name=\"Winslow\"/><ref name=\"Madden\"/><ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by MTV Rapfix\">{{cite web|author=Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by MTV Rapfix|url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/news/946628/nicki-minaj-is-foxy-browns-heart.jhtml#id=1712306 |title= Foxy Brown on MTV Rapfix |publisher= MTV |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 22, 2012}}.</ref> In 2019, Foxy remixed [[Casanova]]'s \u201cSo Brooklyn\u201c.\n\n==Personal life==\nMarchand is of [[Dougla]] (mixed [[Afro-Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Afro-Trinidadian]] and [[Indo-Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Indo-Trinidadian]]) and [[Chinese Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Chinese-Trinidadian]] descent.<ref name=\"outspoken 4\">{{cite web |last=Calloway |first=Sway |authorlink=Sway Calloway |title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Outspoken (Part 4) |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/archive/f/fbrown01/index4.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=2001-05-29 |accessdate=2006-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502130142/http://www.mtv.com/bands/archive/f/fbrown01/index4.jhtml |archivedate=2006-05-02 }}</ref>\n\nShe spent childhood and adolescence in Brooklyn, New York. Her father is Winston Marchand, who pursued a career at ERAC records. \n\nFrom 1999 to 2000, she was engaged to a fellow rapper, [[Kurupt]]. Around 2001, she was engaged to [[Spragga Benz]].<ref name=\"Spragga Benz allmusic\" />\n\nIn 2000, she announced that she was suffering from depression. She subsequently entered drug rehabilitation at Cornell University Medical College to receive treatment for [[opioid addiction]], stating that she could no longer record or perform without resorting to morphine.<ref name=\"Salomon\">{{cite news|last=Salomon|first=Yves|title=Foxy Brown in Rehab|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12057193|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=December 26, 2000|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050922132843/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12057193|archivedate=September 22, 2005}}</ref>\n\nFoxy Brown suffered hearing loss from May 2005 to June 2006. She opted for a hearing aid, and, while recording music, had someone tap beats on her shoulder.<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1518260/20051215/foxy_brown.jhtml|title=Foxy Brown Says She Hasn't Heard A Thing For Six Months|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=2005-12-15|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Foxy Brown Returns: Deafness Cured, She's Back To Work|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1535227/20060627/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2006-06-28|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> She also has a substantial history of assault and menacing.<ref>Larry Celona & Erin Calabrese, [https://nypost.com/2010/07/22/foxy-brown-busted-again-for-attacking-nemesis-neighbor \"Foxy Brown busted again for attacking nemesis neighbor\"], [[New York Post|''New York Post'']], 22 Jul 2010.</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2017, she gave birth to her first child, a girl.<ref name=\"Kwateng-Clark\">{{cite news|url=http://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-welcomed-baby-girl|title=Foxy Brown Welcomed A Baby Girl!|last=Kwateng-Clark|first=Danielle|date=2017-03-03|publisher=Essence|accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles==\nOn January 25, 1997, Brown spat on two hotel employees in Raleigh, North Carolina after they told her they did not have an iron available. When she missed her scheduled court appearance, an arrest warrant was issued. She surrendered on April 30, 1997. She received a 30-day suspended sentence and was ordered to perform 80 hours of community service.<ref name=\"Foxy Brown Turns Herself In\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Turns Herself In|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429116/19970502/story.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-05-02|accessdate=2005-10-06|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060216174048/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429116/19970502/story.jhtml |archivedate = February 16, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> On July 3, 1999, Brown was escorted off the stage by police at a concert in Trinidad and Tobago for using obscene language but was neither charged nor arrested.<ref name=\"Angulo\">{{cite news|last=Angulo|first=Sandra P.|title=Rap Sheet|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84511,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1999-07-12|accessdate=2005-10-06}}</ref> On March 6, 2000, Brown was arrested for driving without a license after crashing her Range Rover in Flatbush, Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Wisloski\">{{cite news|last=Wisloski|first=Jess|title=Foxy racks up 16 N.Y. traffic violations in 3 yrs.|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2007/03/12/2007-03-12_hell_on_wheels.html|work=New York Daily News|date=2007-03-12}}</ref> Brown was involved in an altercation with police at the Norman Manley International Airport in Kingston, Jamaica on July 26, 2002. Brown was accused of illegally evading a body search and punching a policewoman in the stomach. Brown's publicist, Marvette Britto, argued that Brown had felt she was being \"detained\". Brown failed to appear at her hearing on July 28, 2002, and an arrest warrant was issued in late December.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite news|last=Armstrong|first=Mark|title=Foxy Brown Facing Arrest Warrant In Jamaica|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054953|work=Yahoo! Music|date=2002-12-27|accessdate=2008-06-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202232152/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054953|archivedate=2008-12-02}}</ref> Amidst her legal troubles, Brown had an on-air argument with radio host [[Egypt (media personality)|Egypt]] on New York City radio station [[WWPR-FM]] (\"Power 105.1\").<ref name=\"slumz.boxden.com\">{{cite web | url=http://slumz.boxden.com/f5/nov-24-foxy-fudges-on-air-gets-boot-803634 | title=BX Daily Bugle}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Brown pleaded guilty to assaulting a beauty supply store employee.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown pleads not guilty in Fla.|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/2007-03-28-260885186_x.htm|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-03-28}}</ref> Her other arrests during 2007 included leaving New York state without permission during probation,<ref name=\"KCNC-TV\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Pleads Guilty In NYC Court|url=http://cbs4denver.com/entertainment/entertainment_story_060131814.html|work=[[KCNC-TV]]|date=2007-03-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012141018/http://cbs4denver.com/entertainment/entertainment_story_060131814.html|archivedate=2007-10-12}}</ref> hitting a neighbor with a [[BlackBerry]],<ref name=\"Foxy Brown guilty of phone charge\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown guilty of phone charge|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7391741.stm|work=BBC News|date=2008-05-09}}</ref> and almost running over a stroller with a baby inside.<ref name=\"Widdicombe\">{{cite news|last=Widdicombe|first=Ben|title=Rapper's called a wheel menace|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2007/05/15/2007-05-15_rappers_called_a_wheel_menace.html |work=New York Daily News|date=2007-05-15}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that Brown moved from Brooklyn to Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey, without informing officials, but Brown's lawyer Alan Stutman stated that Brown's mother owned the Englewood Cliffs residence in question.<ref name=\"Contrite\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/08/nyregion/08foxy.html|title=Rapper Is Contrite, but Still Gets Year in Jail |last=Hartocollis|first=Anemona|date=September 8, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>{{refn|The February 2007 arrest report for Brown lists her residency as being in Englewood Cliffs.<ref name=\"Smoking Gun\"/>|group=nb}}\n\n[[File:Foxy Brown.jpg|thumb|Mugshot of Brown in 2007]]\nOn August 29, 2004, Brown attacked two manicurists in Chelsea, Manhattan during a dispute over a $20 bill that she refused to pay, and in April 2005 pleaded not guilty to assault charges<ref name=\"Kaufman\">{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Foxy Brown Pleads Not Guilty to Nail-Salon Assault|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1499955/20050412/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-04-12|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> and entered three years of probation effective October 2006.<ref name=\"US rapper Brown put on probation\">{{cite news|title=US rapper Brown put on probation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6081802.stm |work=BBC News|date=2006-10-24}}</ref> For that incident, she took [[anger management]] classes.<ref name=\"Maull\">{{cite news|last=Maull|first=Samuel|title=Foxy Brown Gets Good Probation Report|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/17/AR2007011701239.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-01-17|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> In April 2005, rapper [[Jacki-O]] alleged that she and Brown got into a physical altercation at a recording studio in Miami, Florida, saying that Brown came into the studio during her session and expected her (Jacki-O) to \"bow down\" to her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Foxy Brown and Jacki-O Duke It Out At Miami Studio|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1500805/20050426/story.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-04-26|accessdate=2006-01-01}}</ref> The next month, Brown denied any such altercation in an interview with the Miami, Florida hip-hop radio station [[WEDR]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Foxy Brown And Jacki-O, Ghostface, Nellie McKay, Pras, New Pornographers & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1501204/20050503/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-05-03|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> Joseph Tacopina,<ref name=\"Joseph Tacopina\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tacopinalaw.com/|title=Top Rated New York City Criminal Defense Lawyers &#124; Law Offices of Tacopina & Seigel|website=Tacopinalaw.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref> Brown's attorney, stated on December 6, 2005, that he could no longer communicate with Foxy Brown verbally due to her sudden hearing loss. Judge Melissa Jackson suspended Brown's assault case for two weeks.<ref name=\"Lawyer: Foxy Brown is Deaf\">{{cite news|title=Lawyer: Foxy Brown is Deaf|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60431/lawyer-foxy-brown-is-deaf|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|agency=Associated Press|date=2005-12-06|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2007, New York Criminal Court Judge Melissa Jackson sentenced Foxy Brown to one year in jail for violating her probation that stemmed from the 2004 fight with two manicurists in a New York City nail salon.<ref name=\"MSNBC\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown sentenced to a year in jail|url=http://www.today.com/id/20647922|work=Today.com|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2007-09-07}}</ref> On September 12, 2007, her representatives stated the rapper was not pregnant in response to claims by her lawyer that she was.<ref name=\"Jailed Foxy Brown 'not pregnant'\">{{cite news|title=Jailed Foxy Brown 'not pregnant'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6992526.stm|work=BBC News|date=2007-09-13|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> On October 23, 2007, Brown was given 76 days in solitary confinement due to a physical altercation that took place on October 3, 2007, with another prisoner. According to the prison authorities, Brown, the next day after the incident, was also verbally abusive toward correction officers and refused to take a random drug test.<ref name=\"Scharm\">{{cite news|last=Scharm|first=Jamie|title=Foxy Slammed with Solitary|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/10232007/news/regionalnews/foxy_slammed_with_solitary.htm|work=New York Post|date=2007-10-23}}</ref> Prison authorities reported on November 27 that she was released \"from solitary confinement...for good behavior\",<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown released from solitary confinemen|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/peopleNews/idUSN2751270920071129|work=Billboard|agency=Reuters|date=2007-11-27}}</ref> and Brown was finally released from prison on April 18, 2008.<ref name=\"McGee\">{{cite web|last=McGee|first=Tiffany|last2=Hopkins|first2=Tiffany|title=Foxy Brown's Emotional Release from Prison|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20192748,00.html|work=People|date=2008-04-18}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2010, Brown was arrested and charged with one count of criminal contempt, which is a class E felony (the least severe), for violating an order of protection.<ref name=\"Billboard.com\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/957258/foxy-brown-arrested-in-ny-over-order-of-protection |title=Foxy Brown Arrested In NY Over Order Of Protection |magazine=Billboard.com |date=2009-09-14 |accessdate=2011-08-05}}</ref> The charge stems from an incident during the evening of July 21, 2010, in which it was claimed that Brown swore at and then [[mooned]] her neighbor Arlene Raymond, at whom she had thrown her BlackBerry, in 2007. Following the BlackBerry incident, Raymond sought and received a restraining order against Brown. Following her arrest, Brown appeared in court where she pleaded \"not guilty\" to the charge and was released on a $5,000 bail. If convicted, she faced up to seven years' imprisonment.<ref name=\"Nydailynews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2010/07/22/2010-07-22_foxy_brown_pleads_not_guilty_to_violating_order_of_protection_exposing_herself_t.html#ixzz0uQvUsUMJ |title=Foxy Brown pleads not guilty to violating order of protection, exposing herself to Arlene Raymond |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=2010-07-22 |accessdate=2011-08-05 |location=New York}}</ref> On July 12, 2011,  the charges were dropped.<ref name=\"Gorta\">{{cite news| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/over_the_moon_SCyPM3BdEW3ufx0m5KlvzJ | work=New York Post | first=William J. | last=Gorta|title=Over the moon!|date=13 July 2011|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Lil Kim Feud==\nThe work of [[Lil' Kim]] and Brown were heavily compared which is cited to be the simplist way to describe the relationship between them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Music\u2019s 30 Fiercest Feuds and Beefs|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/musics-30-fiercest-feuds-and-beefs-253226/lil-kim-vs-foxy-brown-253350/|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> \"Things got really personal when shots were fired outside a New York radio station.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Vs. Foxy Brown: Rap Beef|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/hip-hop-rap-feuds/lil-kim-foxy-brown/|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> The two have not resolved the issue, with Foxy siding and collaborating with rapper [[Nicki Minaj]] in her own feud with Kim in recent years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Vs. Foxy Brown: Rap Beef|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/hip-hop-rap-feuds/lil-kim-foxy-brown/|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Following her release from prison, Kim does not acknowledge Brown. Brown, on the other hand, consistently has targeted Kim as a prime basis in her music and concert venues since Kim's prison release.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Bust It Anywhere(Lil Kim Diss)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gpz1_gxqbXc|work=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"XXLmag.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown Jabs Lil' Kim in New Song|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/xxl-magazine/2009/11/foxy-brown-jabs-lil-kim-in-new-song/|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Starbury\">{{cite web|last=Starbury|first=Allen|title=Foxy Brown Disses Lil Kim on New Track: 'You'll Never See Me 'Dancin' With The Stars'|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2009/11/05/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim-on-new-track-youll-never-see-me-dancin-with-the-stars/|website=BallerStatus.com|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HipHopDX.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Hold Yuh (Lil Kim and Nicki Minaj diss)|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/singles/id.12894/title.foxy-brown-hold-yuh-lil-kim-and-nicki-minaj-diss|website=HipHop DX|date=November 26, 2010|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vibe.com\">{{cite web|title=Whoa! Foxy Brown Prepares A 'Christmas Massacre' For Lil' Kim; Dropping Diss Record X-Mas Eve|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/whoa-foxy-brown-prepares-christmas-massacre-lil-kim-dropping-diss-record-x-mas-eve|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=December 20, 2010|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Rap-Up.com\">{{cite web|title=New Music: Foxy Brown \u2013 'Massacre' (Lil' Kim Diss)|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/01/14/new-music-foxy-brown-massacre-lil-kim-diss/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=January 14, 2011|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandler\">{{cite web|last=Chandler|first=D.L.|title=Foxy Brown Disses Lil' Kim... Again|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/08/18/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim/|work=RapFix|publisher=MTV.com|date=August 18, 2011|accessdate=February 13, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513031724/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/08/18/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim/|archivedate=May 13, 2013}}</ref> On May 17, 2012, Kim attended an interview with radio show ''The Breakfast Club''.<ref name=\"breakfast\">{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Talks Nicki Minaj, Azealia Banks, & Scott Storch on 'The Breakfast Club'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/05/17/lil-kim-talks-nicki-minaj-azealia-banks-scott-storch-on-the-breakfast-club/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=May 17, 2012|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> When asked about whether or not she had spoken to Brown at all in recent years, Kim claimed: \"I don't know her. And when I say that; I don't know who she is to these days. I wouldn't even know what her voice sounds like.\"<ref name=\"breakfast\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Foxy Brown discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Ill Na Na]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Chyna Doll (album)|Chyna Doll]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[King Soon Come]]'' (TBA)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]'' (2008)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n* ''[[The Album (The Firm album)|The Album]]'' <small>with The Firm</small> (1997)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Woo (film)|Woo]]''\n|Fianc\u00e9e\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Fade to Black (2004 film)|Fade to Black]]''\n|Herself\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Foxy Brown}}\n*{{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/B/Brown%2C_Foxy/}}\n* [http://www.reverbnation.com/foxybrownmusic Foxy Brown on ReverbNation]\n\n{{Foxy Brown}}\n{{Def Jam Recordings}}\n{{Roc-A-Fella Records}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Foxy}}\n[[Category:Foxy Brown (rapper)| ]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:American rappers of Caribbean descent]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One Music artists]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American rappers of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:American rappers of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Trinidad and Tobago descent]]\n[[Category:Fugitives wanted by Jamaica]]\n[[Category:People from Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Foxy Brown (rapper) songs| ]]\n[[Category:People from Park Slope]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Hardcore hip hop artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:The Firm (hip hop group) members]]\n[[Category:Asian-American female models]]\n[[Category:Hip hop models]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:People of Dougla descent]]\n[[Category:Models from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century women rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women rappers]]\n[[Category:American people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:African-American female rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the rapper|the reggae singer|Foxy Brown (singer)}}\n{{short description|American rapper, actress, and model from New York}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Foxy Brown\n| image              = Foxy brown-03-mika.jpg\n| caption            = Marchand in 1998\n| alias              = {{hlist|Dutchess|Fox Boogie|Ill Na Na<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/374556|title=Dutchess (2)|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref>}}\n| birth_name         = Inga DeCarlo Fung Marchand<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-dad-was-us-trinidad-immigration/|title=Foxy Brown Reveals That Her Dad Was Stopped From Returning To The U.S.|website=Essence.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref><ref name=\"entertainment weekly\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Scott|last2=Serpick|first2=Evan|title=Lil' Brown & Co.|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,280191,00.html|periodical=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|issue=586|date=2001-03-09|accessdate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1978|9|6}}{{refn|An arrest report by the [[Broward County Sheriff's Office]] dated February 16, 2007, listed her birth year as 1978.<ref name=\"Smoking Gun\"/> An article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' from September 8, 2007, stated: \"Ms. Brown, who turned 29 on Thursday [September 6], had tried to conceal her identity by writing her name as Enga rather than Inga, and giving her date of birth as 1980 rather than 1978.\"<ref name=\"Contrite\"/> The website [[AllMusic]] lists her birth date as September 6, 1979.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> An ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' article from March 9, 2001 appears to support the 1979 birth year. In her song \"I Don't Need Nobody\", Marchand raps \"1978 / The year I was born\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UfUlZ7FCGCk \"I Don't Need Nobody\"] on YouTube</ref>|group=nb}}\n| birth_place        =  [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* model\n* actress\n* songwriter\n}}\n| years_active       = 1995\u2013present\n| home_town          = \n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* Black Rose {{small|(current)}}\n* [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]\n* [[Entertainment One Music|Koch]]\n* [[S. Carter Records|S. Carter]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Rush]]\n* [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n* [[Violator (company)|Violator]]{{small| (former)}}\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n*[[The Firm (hip hop group)|The Firm]]\n*[[DJ Clue]]\n*[[Jay-Z]]\n*[[N.O.R.E.]]\n*[[Spragga Benz]]\n*[[Trackmasters]]\n*[[Nicki Minaj]]}}\n| module = {{Infobox person\n| child = yes \n| partner = [[Kurupt]] (1999\u20132000)<br>[[Spragga Benz]] (2001)\n| children = 1\n}}\n}}\n'''Inga DeCarlo Fung Marchand''' (born September 6, 1978), better known by her stage name '''Foxy Brown''', is an American rapper. After signing to [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]] in 1996, she released her debut album, ''[[Ill Na Na]]'', that same year, and was also part of the short-lived rap group [[The Firm (hip hop group)|the Firm]].\n\nHer second album ''[[Chyna Doll (album)|Chyna Doll]]'', arrived in 1999, and her third, the Grammy-nominated ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]'', in 2001.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/foxy-brown | title=Foxy Brown| date=2018-05-22}}</ref>  [[The Album (The Firm album)|The Firm's sole album]] arrived in 1997. Since 2001, she has featured on songs, but has not released any albums. In 2003, she left Def Jam and cancelled the release of her ''Ill Na Na 2'' album, but returned in 2005 once [[Jay-Z]], then the label's president and CEO, signed her again to begin work on her new album ''[[Black Roses (Foxy Brown album)|Black Roses]]''. Her [[mixtape]] ''[[Brooklyn Don Diva]]'' was released in May 2008, and her visual album, ''[[King Soon Come (Foxy Brown album)|King Soon Come]]'', was slated for 2019 release.<ref name=\"Winslow\">{{Cite news|url=https://allhiphop.com/2017/03/02/rapper-foxy-brown-gives-birth-baby-girl/|title=Rapper Foxy Brown Gives Birth To A Baby Girl|last=Winslow|first=Mike|accessdate=August 20, 2017|quote=Foxy Brown is working on her latest album, King Soon Come.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theblackloop.com/wow-foxy-brown-just-gave-birth-baby-girl-shocks-everyone/|title=Wow! Foxy Brown Just Gave Birth To A Baby Girl! Shocks Everyone!|last=Loop|first=The Black|accessdate=August 20, 2017|quote=Congrats to Foxy Brown! Foxy Brown is working on her latest album, King Soon Come.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822175050/https://www.theblackloop.com/wow-foxy-brown-just-gave-birth-baby-girl-shocks-everyone/|archive-date=2017-08-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Madden\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/09/happy-birthday-foxy-brown/|title=Happy Birthday, Foxy Brown!|last=Madden|first=Sidney|accessdate=September 30, 2017|quote=To date, Foxy is said to be working on her fourth studio album, King Soon Come.}}</ref><ref name=\"Clark\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-shares-first-photo-her-adorable-baby-girl|title=Foxy Brown Shares The First Photo Of Her Adorable Baby Girl|last=Clark|first=Danielle Kwateng|accessdate=September 30, 2017|quote=Currently she's working on her fourth studio album.}}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n===1995\u20131997: Early career, ''Ill Na Na'' and The Firm===\nWhile still a teenager, Brown won a talent contest in the [[Park Slope]] neighborhood of Brooklyn, New York. Members of the production team [[Trackmasters]] who were working on [[LL Cool J]]'s ''[[Mr. Smith (album)|Mr. Smith]]'' album were in attendance that night and were impressed enough to invite Brown to rap over \"[[I Shot Ya]].\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Bush|first= John|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29875|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2008|accessdate=2008-05-14}}</ref> She followed this debut with appearances on several [[RIAA certification|RIAA platinum and gold singles]] from other artists, including remixes of songs \"You're Makin' Me High\" by [[Toni Braxton]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> Brown was also featured on the soundtrack to the 1996 film ''[[The Nutty Professor (1996 film)|The Nutty Professor]]'', on the songs \"Touch Me Tease Me\" by [[Case (singer)|Case]] and \"[[Ain't No Nigga]]\" by [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. [{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r236237|pure_url=yes}} \"The Nutty Professor\" \u2013 overview]. [[AllMusic]]: c. 1996.</ref> She became an instant sensation due to being very talented and rapping provocatively at such a young age. The immediate success led to a label bidding war at the beginning of 1996, and in March, [[Def Jam Records]] won and added the then 17-year-old rapper to their roster.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] has been said to have wanted her to join his rap group \u201c[[Junior M.A.F.I.A.]]\u2019 However, due to him no being able to win the bidding war, he settled for Lil\u2019 Kim instead. In 1996, Foxy Brown, Lil' Kim, Da Brat, and Total got together for the recording of Bad Boy's remix of \"No One Else\". This was the only track that Lil' Kim and Foxy Brown appeared on together, the two were friends at the time.\n\nIn 1996, Brown released her debut album ''[[Ill Na Na]]'' to mixed reviews but strong sales. The album sold over 109,000 copies in the first week, and debuted at #7 on the Billboard 200 album charts.<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> The album was heavily produced by Trackmasters, and featured guest appearances from [[Jay-Z]], [[Blackstreet]], [[Method Man]], and [[Kid Capri]].<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Erlewine, Stephen Thomas. [{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r243995|pure_url=yes}} \"Ill Na Na\" \u2013 overview]. [[AllMusic]]</ref> The album was [[RIAA certification|platinum]] and launched two hit singles: \"[[Get Me Home (song)|Get Me Home]]\" (featuring [[Blackstreet]]) and \"I'll Be\" (featuring [[Jay-Z]]).<ref name=\"single charts\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Billboard singles|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p29875|pure_url=yes}}|work= [[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2007-10-10}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of ''Ill Na Na'', Brown joined fellow New York-based hip hop artists, [[Nas]], [[AZ (rapper)|AZ]], and [[Nature (rapper)|Nature]] to form the [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]] known as [[The Firm (hip hop group)|The Firm]]. The album was released via [[Aftermath Records]] and was produced and recorded by the collective team of [[Dr. Dre]], [[the Trackmasters]], and [[Steve Stoute|Steve \"Commissioner\" Stoute]], then of [[Violator Entertainment]]. An early form of The Firm appeared on \"Affirmative Action\" from Nas' second album ''[[It Was Written]]''. A remix of the song and several group [[Freestyle rap|freestyles]] were on the album ''[[The Album (The Firm album)|Nas, Foxy Brown, AZ, and Nature Present The Firm: The Album]]''.<ref name=\"firm\">{{cite web|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|title=The Firm \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p276628|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> The album entered the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart at #1.<ref name=\"The Firm \u2013 Billboard Albums\">{{cite web|title=The Firm \u2013 Billboard Albums|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p276628|pure_url=yes}}|work=Billboard|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1997, she joined the [[spring break]] festivities hosted by MTV in Panama City, Florida, among other performers including rapper [[Snoop Dogg]], pop group [[The Spice Girls]], and rock band [[Stone Temple Pilots]].<ref name=\"MTV News\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown, Spice Girls, Snoop, STP Do Spring Break|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429118/19970313/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-03-13|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> Later, she joined the Smokin' Grooves tour hosted by the [[House of Blues]] with the headlining rap group [[Cypress Hill]], along with other performers like [[Erykah Badu]], [[The Roots]], [[OutKast]], and [[The Pharcyde]], the tour set to begin in [[Boston, Massachusetts]], in the summer of 1997.<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite news|title=Cypress Hill, Erykah Badu, Foxy Brown Join Smokin' Grooves Tour|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425328/19970408/badu_erykah.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-04-08|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> However, after missing several dates in the tour, she left it.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Bows Out of Smokin' Grooves|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429114/19970714/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-07-14|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===1998\u20131999: ''Chyna Doll''===\n''Chyna Doll'' was released in January 1999 and debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200 Album charts<ref>{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Delays second album, Talks Diversity|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429106/19981207/foxy_brown.jhtml | publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1998-12-07|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> which sold 173,000 copies in its opening week.<ref name=\"Boehlert\">{{cite news|last=Boehlert|first=Eric|title=Silk the Shocker|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/foxybrown2/articles/story/5923314/shock_the_shocker|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1999-02-03|accessdate=2008-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080104164212/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/foxybrown2/articles/story/5923314/shock_the_shocker|archive-date=2008-01-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, its sales quickly declined in later weeks.<ref name=\"Promis\">{{cite web|last=Promis|first= Jose F.|title=\"Chyna Doll\" \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r380219|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2007-10-11}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"Hot Spot\", failed to enter the top 50 of the ''Billboard'' pop charts, as did the follow-up single, \"I Can't\" (featuring [[Total (group)|Total]]). ''Chyna Doll'' has been certified [[RIAA Certification|platinum]] after surpassing one million copies sold in shippments.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Gold and Platinum|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Foxy%20Brown&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=12&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=25|publisher=[[RIAA]]|accessdate=2008-02-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924151852/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Foxy%20Brown&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=on&before=on&startMonth=1&endMonth=12&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=25|archivedate=2015-09-24}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1999, Brown stated on ''[[The Ricki Lake Show]]'' that she would appear in the 2000 action film ''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]].'' The role was recast after Brown's legal troubles; actress [[Lucy Liu]] took Brown's place.\n\n===2000\u20132003: ''Broken Silence'' and ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever''===\n{{Main|Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)}}\nIn 2001, Brown released ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]''. The single  \"BK Anthem\" showcased Brown changing to a \"street\" image and giving a tribute to her hometown, Brooklyn, and to famous rappers such as [[The Notorious B.I.G.]] and [[Jay Z]]. The first single from the album was \"[[Oh Yeah (Foxy Brown song)|Oh Yeah]]\", which featured her then-boyfriend, Jamaican [[dancehall]] artist [[Spragga Benz]].<ref name=\"Spragga Benz allmusic\">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|title=Spragga Benz \u2013 Biography|url={{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p173453|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2003|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> The track \"Na Na Be Like\" was produced by Kenya Fame Flames Miller and Nokio from [[Dru Hill]]. \"Na Na Be Like\" was also on the ''Blue Streak Soundtrack''.\n\nThe album debuted on the Billboard Charts at #5, selling 130,000 units its first week. Like previous albums, ''Broken Silence'' also sold over 500,000 records and was certified [[Music recording sales certification|gold]] by the [[RIAA]].\n\nIn the same year, Brown recorded a song for the action-comedy film ''[[Rush Hour 2]]'', ''[[Rush Hour 2 (soundtrack)|Blow My Whistle]]'', which is a collaboration with [[Japanese-American]] [[singer-songwriter]] [[Hikaru Utada]], and was written by Utada herself alongside [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Chad Hugo]]. The song is included on [[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]'s ''[[Rush Hour 2 (soundtrack)|Rush Hour 2 Soundtrack]]'', which peaked the 11th spot on both the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and also the first on the [[Top Soundtracks]]. \"Blow My Whistle\" was produced by [[The Neptunes]].<ref name=\"Rush Hour 2\">''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0266915/soundtrack Rush Hour 2]'' on IMDB.com</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Brown returned to the music scene briefly with her single \"[[Stylin']]\", whose remix featured rappers [[Birdman (rapper)|Birdman]], her brother Gavin, [[Loon (rapper)|Loon]], and [[N.O.R.E.]] It was to be the first single from her upcoming album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever''.<ref name=\"Reid\">{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Cam'ron, Foxy Brown, N.O.R.E. On Illest Tour|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1457742/20020923/cam_ron.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2002-09-23|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> The next year, she was featured on [[DJ Kayslay]]'s single \"Too Much for Me\" from his ''Street Sweeper's Volume One Mixtape''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=DJ Kay Slay Says It's Mo' Artists, Mo' Problems On Legit CDs|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472003/20030520/dj_kayslay.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2003-05-20|accessdate=2008-02-25}}</ref> She also appeared on [[Luther Vandross]]' final studio album ''[[Dance with My Father (album) (redirect)|Dance with My Father]]''.<ref name=\"Jeffries 2003\">{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=Dance with My Father \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r642211|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2003|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> That April, Brown appeared on popular New York radio DJ [[Wendy Williams (radio hostess)|Wendy Williams]]' radio show, and revealed the details of her relationships with [[Lyor Cohen]], president of [[Def Jam Recordings]] at the time, and [[Sean Combs|Sean \"P. Diddy\" Combs]]. Brown accused both of illegally trading her recording masters. She also announced that Cohen had cancelled promotion for her fourth album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever'' over personal disagreements.<ref name=\"Promotion Cancelled\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown's \"Ill Na Na 2\" Shelved Indefinitely|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12037470|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=2003-04-22|accessdate=2008-02-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629144901/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12037470|archivedate=2011-06-29}}</ref> Therefore, \"Stylin'\" was released on the compilation album ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] Presents: Hip Hop Hits Vol. 6'' in December 2002.<ref name=\"Kellman 2002\">{{cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|title=\"The Source Presents: Hip Hop Hits, Vol. 6\" \u2013 Overview|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r620169|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|year=2002|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132006: ''Black Roses''===\nUpon leaving [[Def Jam Recordings]] after her disappointment in the cancelled promotion of her studio album, ''[[Ill Na Na 2: The Fever]]'', Brown began recording in late 2004. Months after, she reunited with [[Jay Z]] after performing dates on his Best of Both World Tours. After signing back to Def Jam under his regime, Brown and Jay Z began work on ''Black Roses'' with production by [[The Neptunes]], [[Kanye West]], [[Timbaland]], [[Trackmasters]], and [[Dave Kelly (producer)|Dave Kelly]]. Brown confirmed guest appearances by [[Barrington Levy]], [[Dido (singer)|Dido]], [[Luther Vandross]], [[Mos Def]], [[Baby Cham]], [[Spragga Benz]], [[Shyne]], [[Big Daddy Kane]], [[Rakim]], [[KRS-One]], [[Roxanne Shante]], and [[Jay Z]] although it is uncertain whether all will make the final cut for the album.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} After suffering from a hearing loss and pushing back release dates for the album, Brown left Def Jam for the second time and launched an independent record label, [[Black Rose Entertainment]], in a distribution deal with [[Koch Records]]. According to Brown, two albums worth of material had been recorded between 2004 and 2007 and she planned to release some of the material onto the street album, ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]''.<ref name=\"Baller Status\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2007/08/14/foxy-brown-leaves-def-jam-inks-label-deal-through-koch// |publisher=Baller Status |date=August 14, 2007 |author=Allen Starbury |title=Foxy Brown Leaves Def Jam; Inks Label Deal Through Koch}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, Brown announced that the title for her upcoming album would be ''Black Roses'', explaining, \"My best friend [[Barrington Levy]] has a song called \"Black Roses.\" He's been traveling all over the world and never seen a black rose in no other garden. When he found his black rose, he knew that shit was special. Y'all niggas can have all the female rappers in the world, but there's only one black rose. I feel that's me.\"<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1493486/20041105/foxy_brown.jhtml/ |publisher=MTV |date=November 5, 2004 |author=Shaheem Reid |title=Foxy Brown Planning Comeback With Help From Jay-Z, Shyne}}</ref> In November 2004, Brown announced that she would be the first artist signed to Jay-Z's upcoming imprint record label [[S. Carter Records]]. Rather than launching the imprint, though, Jay-Z became the new president and CEO of [[Def Jam Records]], where he signed Brown as one of the first artists on his new roster.<ref name=\"SOHH\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/10173 |publisher=SOHH |date=November 6, 2006 |author=Dick Johnson |title=Foxy Brown Served \"Black Roses,\" Gets Axed From Label? |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201218/http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/10173 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> On December 8, 2005, Brown announced she had experienced severe and sudden hearing loss]in both ears and she had not heard another person's voice in six months. Brown put ''Black Roses'' aside during this time.<ref name=\"VH1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1518260/20051215/foxy_brown.jhtml |publisher=VH1 |date=December 15, 2005 |author=Chris Harris |title=Foxy Brown Says She Hasn't Heard A Thing For Six Months}}</ref> In June 2006, Brown said her hearing had been restored through surgery and she was planning to resume recording. Her label did not set a release date, but hoped the album would be out by the end of 2006. They were unsure if the title ''Black Roses'' would be kept.<ref name=\"VH12\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1535227/20060627/foxy_brown.jhtml |publisher=VH1 |date=June 28, 2006 |author=Shaheem Reid |title=Foxy Brown Returns: Deafness Cured, She's Back To Work}}</ref> In November 2006, there was speculation that Jay-Z was disappointed in Foxy Brown's \"lack of productivity on the album\" and was planning to drop her from the Def Jam label. The planned December 2006 release of ''Black Roses'' was cancelled.<ref name=\"SOHH\"/>\n\nOn May 22, 2007, Black Hand Entertainment announced a management deal with Brown, with Chaz Williams as her manager. No release date was set for ''Black Roses'', but Brown said the album was nearly complete.<ref name=\"SOHH2\">{{cite news |url=http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/11684/1 |publisher=VH1 |date=May 23, 2007 |author=Anthony Roberts |title=Foxy Brown Under New Management, Ordered To Submit DNA Sample In Assault Case |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930204727/http://www.sohh.com/articles/article.php/11684/1 |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref> A release date of September 6, 2007, was announced two days later.<ref name=\"Mariel Concepcion\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1051937/foxy-brown-readies-comeback-with-black-roses |work=Billboard |date=May 24, 2007 |author=Mariel Concepcion |title=Foxy Brown Readies Comeback With 'Black Roses'}}</ref> On August 16, 2007, Black Hand Entertainment announced that Brown would leave Def Jam to launch an independent record label, [[Black Rose Entertainment]], distributed by [[Koch Records]]. A street album, ''[[Brooklyn Don Diva]]'', was scheduled with a release date of December 4, 2007, but was delayed until May 13, 2008.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1049862/foxy-brown-joins-koch-records |work=Billboard |date=August 15, 2007 |author=Hillary Crosley |title=Foxy Brown Joins Koch Records}}</ref>\n\n''Black Roses'' release has been pushed back several times. In May 2005, the release date was set for July 26, 2005. The next month, it was pushed back to August 23, 2005. In July 2006, Black Roses had a December 2006 release. In May 2007, Brown announced the album would be released on September 6, 2007. As of August 2007, ''Black Roses'' was rumored to be set for a 2008 release date, but nothing was further confirmed. Brown was expected to first release the street album ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]'' on May 13, 2008, following her April 2008 release from prison. In an interview with Billboard.com, Brown stated that the album is back on track and she personally wants in to drop in August or September 2011, however due to no material being released on the planned dates, yet again the album was shelved.\n\n===2007\u2013present: ''Brooklyn's Don Diva'' and ''King Soon Come''===\nBrown signed to [[Koch Records]] in August 2007.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/> ''Brooklyn's Don Diva'', was released as a street album on May 13, 2008, after many delays triggered by her prison sentence. It contains two previously unreleased  songs from her shelved album ''Ill Na Na 2: The Fever.'' The album peaked at #83 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, #8 on the [[Independent Albums]] chart, and #5 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brooklyn's Don Diva > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r1239535|pure_url=yes}}|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-08-18}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Brown released the diss track \u201cMassacre\u201d, a response to Lil\u2019 Kim's \u201cBlack Friday\u201d. On August 14, 2012, Foxy Brown appeared as a special featured guest on [[Nicki Minaj]]'s [[Pink Friday Tour]] in New York City.<ref name=\"Universalmusic.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.universalmusic.com/news/detail/2147 |title=VIDEO: Nicki Minaj Speaks on Foxy Brown after her \"Pink Friday Tour\" |publisher=Universal Music |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref> Rapper [[AZ (rapper)|AZ]] hinted that she is working on new material with Nicki Minaj.<ref name=\"Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by Nadine Graham Comments\">{{cite web|author=Nadine Graham Comments |url=http://www.theboombox.com/2012/10/22/az-the-firm/ |title=The Firm's 'The Album' 15 Years Later: AZ Speaks on Group's First & Final Project |publisher=The Boombox |date=2012-10-22 |accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref> On August 15, 2013, Foxy Brown appeared on MTV Rapfix and announced her fourth studio album tentatively titled \"Bandz Up\" and a single of the same name, produced by Joe Milly, which was set to be released December 24, 2013, but was not released for unknown reasons. In August 2018, Brown made her first official guest appearance since 2009 on \"Coco Chanel\" from Nicki Minaj's fourth studio album ''[[Queen (Nicki Minaj album)|Queen]]''. Brown is currently back to work on her upcoming 4th visual studio album ''King Soon Come '' <ref name=\"Winslow\"/><ref name=\"Madden\"/><ref name=\"Clark\"/><ref name=\"Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by MTV Rapfix\">{{cite web|author=Oct 22nd 2012 3:46PM by MTV Rapfix|url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/news/946628/nicki-minaj-is-foxy-browns-heart.jhtml#id=1712306 |title= Foxy Brown on MTV Rapfix |publisher= MTV |date=August 15, 2013 |accessdate=December 22, 2012}}.</ref> In 2019, Foxy remixed [[Casanova]]'s \u201cSo Brooklyn\u201c.\n\n==Personal life==\nMarchand is of [[Dougla]] (mixed [[Afro-Trinidadians and Tobagonians|Afro-Trinidadian]] and [[Indo-Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Indo-Trinidadian]]) and [[Chinese Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Chinese-Trinidadian]] descent.<ref name=\"outspoken 4\">{{cite web |last=Calloway |first=Sway |authorlink=Sway Calloway |title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Outspoken (Part 4) |url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/archive/f/fbrown01/index4.jhtml |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=2001-05-29 |accessdate=2006-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060502130142/http://www.mtv.com/bands/archive/f/fbrown01/index4.jhtml |archivedate=2006-05-02 }}</ref>\n\nShe spent childhood and adolescence in Brooklyn, New York. Her father is Winston Marchand, who pursued a career at ERAC records. \n\nFrom 1999 to 2000, she was engaged to a fellow rapper, [[Kurupt]]. Around 2001, she was engaged to [[Spragga Benz]].<ref name=\"Spragga Benz allmusic\" />\n\nIn 2000, she announced that she was suffering from depression. She subsequently entered drug rehabilitation at Cornell University Medical College to receive treatment for [[opioid addiction]], stating that she could no longer record or perform without resorting to morphine.<ref name=\"Salomon\">{{cite news|last=Salomon|first=Yves|title=Foxy Brown in Rehab|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12057193|work=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=December 26, 2000|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050922132843/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12057193|archivedate=September 22, 2005}}</ref>\n\nFoxy Brown suffered hearing loss from May 2005 to June 2006. She opted for a hearing aid, and, while recording music, had someone tap beats on her shoulder.<ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1518260/20051215/foxy_brown.jhtml|title=Foxy Brown Says She Hasn't Heard A Thing For Six Months|last=Harris|first=Chris|date=2005-12-15|publisher=MTV News|accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Foxy Brown Returns: Deafness Cured, She's Back To Work|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1535227/20060627/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2006-06-28|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> She also has a substantial history of assault and menacing.<ref>Larry Celona & Erin Calabrese, [https://nypost.com/2010/07/22/foxy-brown-busted-again-for-attacking-nemesis-neighbor \"Foxy Brown busted again for attacking nemesis neighbor\"], [[New York Post|''New York Post'']], 22 Jul 2010.</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2017, she gave birth to her first child, a girl.<ref name=\"Kwateng-Clark\">{{cite news|url=http://www.essence.com/celebrity/foxy-brown-welcomed-baby-girl|title=Foxy Brown Welcomed A Baby Girl!|last=Kwateng-Clark|first=Danielle|date=2017-03-03|publisher=Essence|accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles==\nOn January 25, 1997, Brown spat on two hotel employees in Raleigh, North Carolina after they told her they did not have an iron available. When she missed her scheduled court appearance, an arrest warrant was issued. She surrendered on April 30, 1997. She received a 30-day suspended sentence and was ordered to perform 80 hours of community service.<ref name=\"Foxy Brown Turns Herself In\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Turns Herself In|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429116/19970502/story.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=1997-05-02|accessdate=2005-10-06|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060216174048/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1429116/19970502/story.jhtml |archivedate = February 16, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> On July 3, 1999, Brown was escorted off the stage by police at a concert in Trinidad and Tobago for using obscene language but was neither charged nor arrested.<ref name=\"Angulo\">{{cite news|last=Angulo|first=Sandra P.|title=Rap Sheet|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84511,00.html|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=1999-07-12|accessdate=2005-10-06}}</ref> On March 6, 2000, Brown was arrested for driving without a license after crashing her Range Rover in Flatbush, Brooklyn.<ref name=\"Wisloski\">{{cite news|last=Wisloski|first=Jess|title=Foxy racks up 16 N.Y. traffic violations in 3 yrs.|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2007/03/12/2007-03-12_hell_on_wheels.html|work=New York Daily News|date=2007-03-12}}</ref> Brown was involved in an altercation with police at the Norman Manley International Airport in Kingston, Jamaica on July 26, 2002. Brown was accused of illegally evading a body search and punching a policewoman in the stomach. Brown's publicist, Marvette Britto, argued that Brown had felt she was being \"detained\". Brown failed to appear at her hearing on July 28, 2002, and an arrest warrant was issued in late December.<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite news|last=Armstrong|first=Mark|title=Foxy Brown Facing Arrest Warrant In Jamaica|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054953|work=Yahoo! Music|date=2002-12-27|accessdate=2008-06-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202232152/http://music.yahoo.com/read/news/12054953|archivedate=2008-12-02}}</ref> Amidst her legal troubles, Brown had an on-air argument with radio host [[Egypt (media personality)|Egypt]] on New York City radio station [[WWPR-FM]] (\"Power 105.1\").<ref name=\"slumz.boxden.com\">{{cite web | url=http://slumz.boxden.com/f5/nov-24-foxy-fudges-on-air-gets-boot-803634 | title=BX Daily Bugle}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2007, Brown pleaded guilty to assaulting a beauty supply store employee.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown pleads not guilty in Fla.|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/2007-03-28-260885186_x.htm|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-03-28}}</ref> Her other arrests during 2007 included leaving New York state without permission during probation,<ref name=\"KCNC-TV\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown Pleads Guilty In NYC Court|url=http://cbs4denver.com/entertainment/entertainment_story_060131814.html|work=[[KCNC-TV]]|date=2007-03-01|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012141018/http://cbs4denver.com/entertainment/entertainment_story_060131814.html|archivedate=2007-10-12}}</ref> hitting a neighbor with a [[BlackBerry]],<ref name=\"Foxy Brown guilty of phone charge\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown guilty of phone charge|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7391741.stm|work=BBC News|date=2008-05-09}}</ref> and almost running over a stroller with a baby inside.<ref name=\"Widdicombe\">{{cite news|last=Widdicombe|first=Ben|title=Rapper's called a wheel menace|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2007/05/15/2007-05-15_rappers_called_a_wheel_menace.html |work=New York Daily News|date=2007-05-15}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' reported that Brown moved from Brooklyn to Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey, without informing officials, but Brown's lawyer Alan Stutman stated that Brown's mother owned the Englewood Cliffs residence in question.<ref name=\"Contrite\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/08/nyregion/08foxy.html|title=Rapper Is Contrite, but Still Gets Year in Jail |last=Hartocollis|first=Anemona|date=September 8, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=December 31, 2009}}</ref>{{refn|The February 2007 arrest report for Brown lists her residency as being in Englewood Cliffs.<ref name=\"Smoking Gun\"/>|group=nb}}\n\n[[File:Foxy Brown.jpg|thumb|Mugshot of Brown in 2007]]\nOn August 29, 2004, Brown attacked two manicurists in Chelsea, Manhattan during a dispute over a $20 bill that she refused to pay, and in April 2005 pleaded not guilty to assault charges<ref name=\"Kaufman\">{{cite news|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|title=Foxy Brown Pleads Not Guilty to Nail-Salon Assault|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1499955/20050412/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-04-12|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> and entered three years of probation effective October 2006.<ref name=\"US rapper Brown put on probation\">{{cite news|title=US rapper Brown put on probation|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6081802.stm |work=BBC News|date=2006-10-24}}</ref> For that incident, she took [[anger management]] classes.<ref name=\"Maull\">{{cite news|last=Maull|first=Samuel|title=Foxy Brown Gets Good Probation Report|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/17/AR2007011701239.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-01-17|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> In April 2005, rapper [[Jacki-O]] alleged that she and Brown got into a physical altercation at a recording studio in Miami, Florida, saying that Brown came into the studio during her session and expected her (Jacki-O) to \"bow down\" to her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|title=Foxy Brown and Jacki-O Duke It Out At Miami Studio|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1500805/20050426/story.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-04-26|accessdate=2006-01-01}}</ref> The next month, Brown denied any such altercation in an interview with the Miami, Florida hip-hop radio station [[WEDR]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Foxy Brown And Jacki-O, Ghostface, Nellie McKay, Pras, New Pornographers & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1501204/20050503/foxy_brown.jhtml|publisher=[[MTV News]]|date=2005-05-03|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> Joseph Tacopina,<ref name=\"Joseph Tacopina\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tacopinalaw.com/|title=Top Rated New York City Criminal Defense Lawyers &#124; Law Offices of Tacopina & Seigel|website=Tacopinalaw.com|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref> Brown's attorney, stated on December 6, 2005, that he could no longer communicate with Foxy Brown verbally due to her sudden hearing loss. Judge Melissa Jackson suspended Brown's assault case for two weeks.<ref name=\"Lawyer: Foxy Brown is Deaf\">{{cite news|title=Lawyer: Foxy Brown is Deaf|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60431/lawyer-foxy-brown-is-deaf|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|agency=Associated Press|date=2005-12-06|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref>\n\nOn September 7, 2007, New York Criminal Court Judge Melissa Jackson sentenced Foxy Brown to one year in jail for violating her probation that stemmed from the 2004 fight with two manicurists in a New York City nail salon.<ref name=\"MSNBC\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown sentenced to a year in jail|url=http://www.today.com/id/20647922|work=Today.com|agency=Associated Press|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2007-09-07}}</ref> On September 12, 2007, her representatives stated the rapper was not pregnant in response to claims by her lawyer that she was.<ref name=\"Jailed Foxy Brown 'not pregnant'\">{{cite news|title=Jailed Foxy Brown 'not pregnant'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6992526.stm|work=BBC News|date=2007-09-13|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> On October 23, 2007, Brown was given 76 days in solitary confinement due to a physical altercation that took place on October 3, 2007, with another prisoner. According to the prison authorities, Brown, the next day after the incident, was also verbally abusive toward correction officers and refused to take a random drug test.<ref name=\"Scharm\">{{cite news|last=Scharm|first=Jamie|title=Foxy Slammed with Solitary|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/10232007/news/regionalnews/foxy_slammed_with_solitary.htm|work=New York Post|date=2007-10-23}}</ref> Prison authorities reported on November 27 that she was released \"from solitary confinement...for good behavior\",<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|title=Foxy Brown released from solitary confinemen|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/peopleNews/idUSN2751270920071129|work=Billboard|agency=Reuters|date=2007-11-27}}</ref> and Brown was finally released from prison on April 18, 2008.<ref name=\"McGee\">{{cite web|last=McGee|first=Tiffany|last2=Hopkins|first2=Tiffany|title=Foxy Brown's Emotional Release from Prison|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20192748,00.html|work=People|date=2008-04-18}}</ref>\n\nOn July 22, 2010, Brown was arrested and charged with one count of criminal contempt, which is a class E felony (the least severe), for violating an order of protection.<ref name=\"Billboard.com\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/957258/foxy-brown-arrested-in-ny-over-order-of-protection |title=Foxy Brown Arrested In NY Over Order Of Protection |magazine=Billboard.com |date=2009-09-14 |accessdate=2011-08-05}}</ref> The charge stems from an incident during the evening of July 21, 2010, in which it was claimed that Brown swore at and then [[mooned]] her neighbor Arlene Raymond, at whom she had thrown her BlackBerry, in 2007. Following the BlackBerry incident, Raymond sought and received a restraining order against Brown. Following her arrest, Brown appeared in court where she pleaded \"not guilty\" to the charge and was released on a $5,000 bail. If convicted, she faced up to seven years' imprisonment.<ref name=\"Nydailynews.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2010/07/22/2010-07-22_foxy_brown_pleads_not_guilty_to_violating_order_of_protection_exposing_herself_t.html#ixzz0uQvUsUMJ |title=Foxy Brown pleads not guilty to violating order of protection, exposing herself to Arlene Raymond |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=2010-07-22 |accessdate=2011-08-05 |location=New York}}</ref> On July 12, 2011,  the charges were dropped.<ref name=\"Gorta\">{{cite news| url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/over_the_moon_SCyPM3BdEW3ufx0m5KlvzJ | work=New York Post | first=William J. | last=Gorta|title=Over the moon!|date=13 July 2011|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Lil Kim Feud==\nThe work of [[Lil' Kim]] and Brown was heavily compared when they both started. \"Things got really personal when shots were fired outside a New York radio station.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Vs. Foxy Brown: Rap Beef|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/hip-hop-rap-feuds/lil-kim-foxy-brown/|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> The two have not resolved the issue, with Foxy siding and collaborating with rapper [[Nicki Minaj]] in her own feud with Kim in recent years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Vs. Foxy Brown: Rap Beef|url=https://www.capitalxtra.com/features/lists/hip-hop-rap-feuds/lil-kim-foxy-brown/|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Following her release from prison, Kim does not acknowledge Brown. Brown, on the other hand, consistently has targeted Kim as a prime basis in her music and concert venues since Kim's prison release.<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Bust It Anywhere(Lil Kim Diss)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gpz1_gxqbXc|work=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"XXLmag.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown Jabs Lil' Kim in New Song|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/xxl-magazine/2009/11/foxy-brown-jabs-lil-kim-in-new-song/|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=November 4, 2009|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Starbury\">{{cite web|last=Starbury|first=Allen|title=Foxy Brown Disses Lil Kim on New Track: 'You'll Never See Me 'Dancin' With The Stars'|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2009/11/05/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim-on-new-track-youll-never-see-me-dancin-with-the-stars/|website=BallerStatus.com|date=November 5, 2009|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"HipHopDX.com\">{{cite web|title=Foxy Brown \u2013 Hold Yuh (Lil Kim and Nicki Minaj diss)|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/singles/id.12894/title.foxy-brown-hold-yuh-lil-kim-and-nicki-minaj-diss|website=HipHop DX|date=November 26, 2010|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vibe.com\">{{cite web|title=Whoa! Foxy Brown Prepares A 'Christmas Massacre' For Lil' Kim; Dropping Diss Record X-Mas Eve|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/whoa-foxy-brown-prepares-christmas-massacre-lil-kim-dropping-diss-record-x-mas-eve|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=December 20, 2010|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Rap-Up.com\">{{cite web|title=New Music: Foxy Brown \u2013 'Massacre' (Lil' Kim Diss)|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/01/14/new-music-foxy-brown-massacre-lil-kim-diss/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=January 14, 2011|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandler\">{{cite web|last=Chandler|first=D.L.|title=Foxy Brown Disses Lil' Kim... Again|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/08/18/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim/|work=RapFix|publisher=MTV.com|date=August 18, 2011|accessdate=February 13, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513031724/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/08/18/foxy-brown-disses-lil-kim/|archivedate=May 13, 2013}}</ref> On May 17, 2012, Kim attended an interview with radio show ''The Breakfast Club''.<ref name=\"breakfast\">{{cite web|title=Lil' Kim Talks Nicki Minaj, Azealia Banks, & Scott Storch on 'The Breakfast Club'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/05/17/lil-kim-talks-nicki-minaj-azealia-banks-scott-storch-on-the-breakfast-club/|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=May 17, 2012|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> When asked about whether or not she had spoken to Brown at all in recent years, Kim claimed: \"I don't know her. And when I say that; I don't know who she is to these days. I wouldn't even know what her voice sounds like.\"<ref name=\"breakfast\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Foxy Brown discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Ill Na Na]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Chyna Doll (album)|Chyna Doll]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Broken Silence (Foxy Brown album)|Broken Silence]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[King Soon Come]]'' (TBA)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''[[Brooklyn's Don Diva]]'' (2008)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n* ''[[The Album (The Firm album)|The Album]]'' <small>with The Firm</small> (1997)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Woo (film)|Woo]]''\n|Fianc\u00e9e\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Fade to Black (2004 film)|Fade to Black]]''\n|Herself\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Foxy Brown}}\n*{{Curlie|Arts/Music/Bands_and_Artists/B/Brown%2C_Foxy/}}\n* [http://www.reverbnation.com/foxybrownmusic Foxy Brown on ReverbNation]\n\n{{Foxy Brown}}\n{{Def Jam Recordings}}\n{{Roc-A-Fella Records}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Foxy}}\n[[Category:Foxy Brown (rapper)| ]]\n[[Category:1978 births]